{"id":"1806.05786","submitter":"Ting-Wen Lan","authors":"Ting-Wen Lan and Houjun Mo","title":"The circumgalactic medium of eBOSS emission line galaxies: signatures of\n  galactic outflows in gas distribution and kinematics","comments":"14 pages, 8 figures, matched the accepted version","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.3847/1538-4357/aadc08","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.GA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We study the distribution and kinematics of the cool circumgalactic medium\n(CGM) of emission line galaxies (ELGs) traced by metal absorption lines. Using\nabout 200,000 ELGs from SDSS-IV eBOSS and half a million background quasars\nfrom SDSS, we measure the median absorption strength of MgII and FeII lines in\nquasar spectra for impact parameters ranging from 10 kpc to 1 Mpc. For\ncomparison we measure the same quantity around luminous red galaxies (LRGs). On\nscales greater than 100 kpc both ELGs and LRGs exhibit similar absorption\nprofiles. However, metal absorption is 5-10 times stronger around ELGs on\nsmaller scales. The metal absorption strength is anisotropic, with an excess\nalong the minor-axis of the galaxies, indicating an outflow origin of the\nabsorbing gas. The ratio between the velocity dispersion of the cool CGM and\nthat of its host dark matter halo is about one for ELGs but about half for\nLRGs. These results show that the dichotomy of galaxy types is reflected in\nboth the density distribution and kinematics of the CGM traced by metal\nabsorption lines. Our results provide strong evidence that the CGM of ELGs is\nenriched by gas outflows generated by star formation.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 15 Jun 2018 02:07:06 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 17 Sep 2018 02:42:32 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-10-17"}
