{"id":"1806.05936","submitter":"Laurent Bienvenu","authors":"Laurent Bienvenu, Barbara F. Csima, Matthew Harrison-Trainor","title":"Optimal bounds for single-source Kolmogorov extractors","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.LO","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  The rate of randomness (or dimension) of a string $\\sigma$ is the ratio\n$C(\\sigma)/|\\sigma|$ where $C(\\sigma)$ is the Kolmogorov complexity of\n$\\sigma$. While it is known that a single computable transformation cannot\nincrease the rate of randomness of all sequences, Fortnow, Hitchcock, Pavan,\nVinodchandran, and Wang showed that for any $0<\\alpha<\\beta<1$, there are a\nfinite number of computable transformations such that any string of rate at\nleast $\\alpha$ is turned into a string of rate at least $\\beta$ by one of these\ntransformations. However, their proof only gives very loose bounds on the\ncorrespondence between the number of transformations and the increase of rate\nof randomness one can achieve. By translating this problem to combinatorics on\n(hyper)graphs, we provide a tight bound, namely: Using $k$ transformations, one\ncan get an increase from rate $\\alpha$ to any rate $\\beta <\nk\\alpha/(1+(k-1)\\alpha)$, and this is optimal.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 15 Jun 2018 12:50:31 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sun, 24 Nov 2019 17:20:14 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-11-26"}
